<div class="spacer"></div>

<p>From the days of yore to today, crewel embroidery has been used to create fine textiles such as bed hangings, curtains, cushions, and even fashion apparel and accessories. Traditionally crewel embroidery is done on a tightly woven linen, however today's crewel back-cloths include jute, silk, twill, and even velvet. A sturdy, firm fabric is required in order to sufficiently support the weight of the wool yarns. </p>
<div class="spacer"></div>

<div class="row" align="center">
	<div class="col-md-6">
